[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":760},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F":735,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F":744},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200904\u002F1772972600\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":718,"date":719,"description":720,"extension":721,"lang":722,"meta":723,"navigation":190,"path":724,"readingMinutes":725,"seo":726,"standalone":727,"stem":728,"tags":729,"tldr":732,"updated":719,"url":733,"__hash__":734},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing.md","JavaScript Objects: Call by Reference or Call by Sharing? (Core Concepts 29)","1000855255",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":713},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,35,93,96,99,237,259,283,395,403,411,533,543,655,666,669,679,689,696,700,709],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"This time let's talk about something that confuses a lot of people — is JavaScript Call by Reference or Call by Sharing?",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"evaluation-strategy","Evaluation strategy",[17,25,26,27,34],{},"An evaluation strategy is basically how a programming language works under the hood. If you check the ",[28,29,33],"a",{"href":30,"rel":31},"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FEvaluation_strategy",[32],"nofollow","Wikipedia page",", you'll find a whole list of these terms:",[36,37,38,62,79],"ul",{},[39,40,41,42],"li",{},"Strict evaluation\n",[36,43,44,47,50,53,56,59],{},[39,45,46],{},"Applicative order",[39,48,49],{},"Call by value",[39,51,52],{},"Call by reference",[39,54,55],{},"Call by sharing",[39,57,58],{},"Call by copy-restore",[39,60,61],{},"Partial evaluation",[39,63,64,65],{},"Non-strict evaluation\n",[36,66,67,70,73,76],{},[39,68,69],{},"Normal order",[39,71,72],{},"Call by name",[39,74,75],{},"Call by need",[39,77,78],{},"Call by macro expansion",[39,80,81,82],{},"Nondeterministic strategies\n",[36,83,84,87,90],{},[39,85,86],{},"Full β-reduction",[39,88,89],{},"Call by future",[39,91,92],{},"Optimistic evaluation",[17,94,95],{},"That's a lot. But here we only care about three of them — Call by value, Call by reference, and Call by sharing.",[17,97,98],{},"Let's start with Call by value (also known as pass by value). Take a look at this example:",[100,101,106],"pre",{"className":102,"code":103,"language":104,"meta":105,"style":105},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function fn (a, b) {\n  var temp = 100;\n  a = temp;\n  b = a;\n}\n\nvar x = 10;\nvar y = 20;\n\nfn(x, y);\n","js","",[107,108,109,138,157,168,179,185,192,208,223,228],"code",{"__ignoreMap":105},[110,111,114,118,122,126,129,132,135],"span",{"class":112,"line":113},"line",1,[110,115,117],{"class":116},"sWyjQ","function",[110,119,121],{"class":120},"sj_SG"," fn",[110,123,125],{"class":124},"sMAXC"," (",[110,127,28],{"class":128},"s_sBn",[110,130,131],{"class":124},", ",[110,133,134],{"class":128},"b",[110,136,137],{"class":124},") {\n",[110,139,141,144,147,150,154],{"class":112,"line":140},2,[110,142,143],{"class":116},"  var",[110,145,146],{"class":124}," temp ",[110,148,149],{"class":116},"=",[110,151,153],{"class":152},"sCcAr"," 100",[110,155,156],{"class":124},";\n",[110,158,160,163,165],{"class":112,"line":159},3,[110,161,162],{"class":124},"  a ",[110,164,149],{"class":116},[110,166,167],{"class":124}," temp;\n",[110,169,171,174,176],{"class":112,"line":170},4,[110,172,173],{"class":124},"  b ",[110,175,149],{"class":116},[110,177,178],{"class":124}," a;\n",[110,180,182],{"class":112,"line":181},5,[110,183,184],{"class":124},"}\n",[110,186,188],{"class":112,"line":187},6,[110,189,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},true,"\n",[110,193,195,198,201,203,206],{"class":112,"line":194},7,[110,196,197],{"class":116},"var",[110,199,200],{"class":124}," x ",[110,202,149],{"class":116},[110,204,205],{"class":152}," 10",[110,207,156],{"class":124},[110,209,211,213,216,218,221],{"class":112,"line":210},8,[110,212,197],{"class":116},[110,214,215],{"class":124}," y ",[110,217,149],{"class":116},[110,219,220],{"class":152}," 20",[110,222,156],{"class":124},[110,224,226],{"class":112,"line":225},9,[110,227,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,229,231,234],{"class":112,"line":230},10,[110,232,233],{"class":120},"fn",[110,235,236],{"class":124},"(x, y);\n",[17,238,239,240,243,244,247,248,250,251,253,254,243,256,258],{},"Quick walkthrough of what's going on here. I created two global variables, ",[107,241,242],{},"x"," and ",[107,245,246],{},"y",", and a function called ",[107,249,233],{}," that takes two parameters. Then I called ",[107,252,233],{}," and passed in ",[107,255,242],{},[107,257,246],{},".",[17,260,261,262,264,265,268,269,272,273,243,275,277,278,243,280,282],{},"Inside ",[107,263,233],{}," we do a few things. First we create a local variable ",[107,266,267],{},"temp"," and assign it ",[107,270,271],{},"100",". Then we reassign the parameters ",[107,274,28],{},[107,276,134],{},". So after all that runs, what do you think ",[107,279,242],{},[107,281,246],{}," end up as?",[100,284,286],{"className":102,"code":285,"language":104,"meta":105,"style":105},"function fn (a, b) {\n  var temp = 100;\n  a = temp;\n  b = a;\n}\n\nvar x = 10;\nvar y = 20;\n\nfn(x, y);\n\nconsole.log(x, y); \u002F\u002F 10, 20\n",[107,287,288,304,316,324,332,336,340,352,364,368,374,379],{"__ignoreMap":105},[110,289,290,292,294,296,298,300,302],{"class":112,"line":113},[110,291,117],{"class":116},[110,293,121],{"class":120},[110,295,125],{"class":124},[110,297,28],{"class":128},[110,299,131],{"class":124},[110,301,134],{"class":128},[110,303,137],{"class":124},[110,305,306,308,310,312,314],{"class":112,"line":140},[110,307,143],{"class":116},[110,309,146],{"class":124},[110,311,149],{"class":116},[110,313,153],{"class":152},[110,315,156],{"class":124},[110,317,318,320,322],{"class":112,"line":159},[110,319,162],{"class":124},[110,321,149],{"class":116},[110,323,167],{"class":124},[110,325,326,328,330],{"class":112,"line":170},[110,327,173],{"class":124},[110,329,149],{"class":116},[110,331,178],{"class":124},[110,333,334],{"class":112,"line":181},[110,335,184],{"class":124},[110,337,338],{"class":112,"line":187},[110,339,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,341,342,344,346,348,350],{"class":112,"line":194},[110,343,197],{"class":116},[110,345,200],{"class":124},[110,347,149],{"class":116},[110,349,205],{"class":152},[110,351,156],{"class":124},[110,353,354,356,358,360,362],{"class":112,"line":210},[110,355,197],{"class":116},[110,357,215],{"class":124},[110,359,149],{"class":116},[110,361,220],{"class":152},[110,363,156],{"class":124},[110,365,366],{"class":112,"line":225},[110,367,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,369,370,372],{"class":112,"line":230},[110,371,233],{"class":120},[110,373,236],{"class":124},[110,375,377],{"class":112,"line":376},11,[110,378,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,380,382,385,388,391],{"class":112,"line":381},12,[110,383,384],{"class":124},"console.",[110,386,387],{"class":120},"log",[110,389,390],{"class":124},"(x, y); ",[110,392,394],{"class":393},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 10, 20\n",[17,396,397,398,243,400,402],{},"Here, a function's parameters are kind of like declaring brand new variables. So ",[107,399,28],{},[107,401,134],{}," each live in their own separate memory location. That's the whole idea behind Call by value — you're passing in a \"copy,\" and the actual value gets stored in a different memory slot. In plainer terms: changing the copy doesn't touch the original.",[17,404,405,406,410],{},"Next up is Call by reference, which is basically the opposite. Here, if you modify the value you passed in, it ",[407,408,409],"em",{},"does"," affect the original variable. Like this:",[100,412,414],{"className":102,"code":413,"language":104,"meta":105,"style":105},"function fn (a) {\n  var temp = 100;\n  a.x = temp;\n  a.y = a.x;\n}\n\nvar obj = {\n  x: 10,\n  y: 20,\n}\n\nfn(obj);\n\nconsole.log(obj.x, obj.y); \u002F\u002F 100, 100\n",[107,415,416,428,440,449,459,463,467,479,490,500,504,508,515,520],{"__ignoreMap":105},[110,417,418,420,422,424,426],{"class":112,"line":113},[110,419,117],{"class":116},[110,421,121],{"class":120},[110,423,125],{"class":124},[110,425,28],{"class":128},[110,427,137],{"class":124},[110,429,430,432,434,436,438],{"class":112,"line":140},[110,431,143],{"class":116},[110,433,146],{"class":124},[110,435,149],{"class":116},[110,437,153],{"class":152},[110,439,156],{"class":124},[110,441,442,445,447],{"class":112,"line":159},[110,443,444],{"class":124},"  a.x ",[110,446,149],{"class":116},[110,448,167],{"class":124},[110,450,451,454,456],{"class":112,"line":170},[110,452,453],{"class":124},"  a.y ",[110,455,149],{"class":116},[110,457,458],{"class":124}," a.x;\n",[110,460,461],{"class":112,"line":181},[110,462,184],{"class":124},[110,464,465],{"class":112,"line":187},[110,466,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,468,469,471,474,476],{"class":112,"line":194},[110,470,197],{"class":116},[110,472,473],{"class":124}," obj ",[110,475,149],{"class":116},[110,477,478],{"class":124}," {\n",[110,480,481,484,487],{"class":112,"line":210},[110,482,483],{"class":124},"  x: ",[110,485,486],{"class":152},"10",[110,488,489],{"class":124},",\n",[110,491,492,495,498],{"class":112,"line":225},[110,493,494],{"class":124},"  y: ",[110,496,497],{"class":152},"20",[110,499,489],{"class":124},[110,501,502],{"class":112,"line":230},[110,503,184],{"class":124},[110,505,506],{"class":112,"line":376},[110,507,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,509,510,512],{"class":112,"line":381},[110,511,233],{"class":120},[110,513,514],{"class":124},"(obj);\n",[110,516,518],{"class":112,"line":517},13,[110,519,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,521,523,525,527,530],{"class":112,"line":522},14,[110,524,384],{"class":124},[110,526,387],{"class":120},[110,528,529],{"class":124},"(obj.x, obj.y); ",[110,531,532],{"class":393},"\u002F\u002F 100, 100\n",[17,534,535,536,538,539,542],{},"So far this looks exactly like Call by reference. But here's the interesting part — what if, based on that same idea, we assign ",[107,537,28],{}," a brand new object inside the function? Will the outer ",[107,540,541],{},"obj"," change along with it?",[100,544,546],{"className":102,"code":545,"language":104,"meta":105,"style":105},"function fn (a) {\n  a = {\n    b: 100,\n    c: 50\n  }\n}\n\nvar obj = {\n  x: 10,\n  y: 20,\n}\n\nfn(obj);\n\nconsole.log(obj); \u002F\u002F { x: 10, y: 20, }\n",[107,547,548,560,568,577,585,590,594,598,608,616,624,628,632,638,642],{"__ignoreMap":105},[110,549,550,552,554,556,558],{"class":112,"line":113},[110,551,117],{"class":116},[110,553,121],{"class":120},[110,555,125],{"class":124},[110,557,28],{"class":128},[110,559,137],{"class":124},[110,561,562,564,566],{"class":112,"line":140},[110,563,162],{"class":124},[110,565,149],{"class":116},[110,567,478],{"class":124},[110,569,570,573,575],{"class":112,"line":159},[110,571,572],{"class":124},"    b: ",[110,574,271],{"class":152},[110,576,489],{"class":124},[110,578,579,582],{"class":112,"line":170},[110,580,581],{"class":124},"    c: ",[110,583,584],{"class":152},"50\n",[110,586,587],{"class":112,"line":181},[110,588,589],{"class":124},"  }\n",[110,591,592],{"class":112,"line":187},[110,593,184],{"class":124},[110,595,596],{"class":112,"line":194},[110,597,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,599,600,602,604,606],{"class":112,"line":210},[110,601,197],{"class":116},[110,603,473],{"class":124},[110,605,149],{"class":116},[110,607,478],{"class":124},[110,609,610,612,614],{"class":112,"line":225},[110,611,483],{"class":124},[110,613,486],{"class":152},[110,615,489],{"class":124},[110,617,618,620,622],{"class":112,"line":230},[110,619,494],{"class":124},[110,621,497],{"class":152},[110,623,489],{"class":124},[110,625,626],{"class":112,"line":376},[110,627,184],{"class":124},[110,629,630],{"class":112,"line":381},[110,631,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,633,634,636],{"class":112,"line":517},[110,635,233],{"class":120},[110,637,514],{"class":124},[110,639,640],{"class":112,"line":522},[110,641,191],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":190},[110,643,645,647,649,652],{"class":112,"line":644},15,[110,646,384],{"class":124},[110,648,387],{"class":120},[110,650,651],{"class":124},"(obj); ",[110,653,654],{"class":393},"\u002F\u002F { x: 10, y: 20, }\n",[17,656,657,658,661,662,665],{},"You'd expect the result to become ",[107,659,660],{},"{ b: 100, c: 50 }",", right? After all, Call by reference is supposed to mean the whole original reference gets passed through. But instead it stays as ",[107,663,664],{},"{ x: 10, y: 20, }",". So what's going on?",[17,667,668],{},"The thing is, JavaScript isn't actually Call by reference — Wikipedia describes it as Call by sharing. Here's the explanation straight from Wikipedia:",[670,671,672],"blockquote",{},[17,673,674,675,678],{},"Call by sharing... means that values are based on a shallow copy. ",[110,676,677],{},"In practice"," if the called function modifies the shared object, the caller sees the change (because the object is shared, not copied).",[17,680,681,682,684,685,688],{},"Applying that to the code above: we can pass a shared object into ",[107,683,233],{}," and modify it, and the caller sees those changes. But we can ",[407,686,687],{},"also"," reassign that parameter to point at a totally new object — and once we do, it's a brand new reference that has nothing to do with the original.",[17,690,691,692,695],{},"So from now on, whenever you see a fresh ",[107,693,694],{},"{ }",", just remember — that's a new reference.",[12,697,699],{"id":698},"references","References",[36,701,702],{},[39,703,704],{},[28,705,708],{"href":706,"rel":707},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[32],"JavaScript Core Course (in Mandarin)",[710,711,712],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}",{"title":105,"searchDepth":140,"depth":140,"links":714},[715,716,717],{"id":14,"depth":140,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":140,"text":23},{"id":698,"depth":140,"text":699},"JavaScript","2020-09-04 21:36:03","Is JavaScript Call by Reference or Call by Sharing? In this post we walk through evaluation strategies — Call by value, Call by reference, and Call by sharing — with simple examples, and figure out which one JavaScript actually uses when you pass objects around.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing","3",{"title":6,"description":720},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing",[718,730,731],"JavaScript Core Concepts","Objects",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F04\u002Fjavascript-core-29-objects-call-by-sharing\u002F","zAN8Jo-WIRx_5M7-3SyJVWsx30DKSxaOH0cUOlqBXRM",{"newer":736,"older":740},{"url":737,"title":738,"date":739},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-core-30-object-shallow-deep-copy\u002F","JavaScript Core Concepts (30): Shallow Copy vs Deep Copy for Objects","2020-09-05 23:22:53",{"url":741,"title":742,"date":743},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F08\u002F31\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-30-game-loop\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (30) - The Game Loop","2020-08-31 13:45:57",[745,750,755],{"url":746,"title":747,"date":748,"readingMinutes":749},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":751,"title":752,"date":753,"readingMinutes":754},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":756,"title":757,"date":758,"readingMinutes":759},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784010277410]